answers.body_markdown:
It depends on your data.

A _CSV_ can be trivial if your data may contain commas.

You could implement a _[TSV](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tab-separated_values)_, which uses the _tab_ character.

_[Wikipedia &amp;ndash; Delimiter-separated values](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delimiter-separated_values)_.

&gt; _&quot;... I would appreciate it if someone could provide me with a simple example and explain the recommended approach to efficiently read, write, and process CSV files into arrays in Java.&quot;_

Here is a basic read and write, using a _TSV_ structure.

```java
void append(String[] strings, File file) throws IOException {
    try (FileWriter writer = new FileWriter(file, true)) {
        writer.write(String.join(&quot;\t&quot;, strings));
        writer.write(System.lineSeparator());
    }
}

List&lt;String[]&gt; read(File file) throws IOException {
    try (BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file))) {
        List&lt;String[]&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
        String line;
        while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null)
            list.add(line.split(&quot;\t&quot;, -1));
        return list;
    }
}
```

And, here is a usage.

```java
File file = new File(&quot;files/data.tsv&quot;);
append(new String[] { &quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;, &quot;c&quot; }, file);
append(new String[] { &quot;d&quot;, &quot;e&quot;, &quot;f&quot; }, file);
List&lt;String[]&gt; list = read(file);
for (String[] strings : list)
    System.out.println(Arrays.toString(strings));
```

